'''Murphy's petrel''' ('''''Pterodroma ultima''''') is a species of [[seabird]] and a member of the [[gadfly petrel]]s. The [[bird]] is 38–41 cm length, with a 97 cm wingspan, and weighs about 360 g.<ref name=HBW>{{cite book |year=1992 |title=[[Handbook of the Birds of the World]] |editor1=del Hoyo, J. |editor2=Elliott, A. |editor3=Sargatal, J. |publisher=Lynx Edicions |location=Barcelona |isbn= |volume=1: Ostrich to Ducks |chapter= |pages= |chapter-url=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=The Sibley Guide to Birds|last=Sibley|first=David Allen|publisher=Knopf|year=2014|isbn=978-0-307-95790-0|location=New York|page=71}}</ref> Its plumage is all dark sooty-grey, except for a pale chin, and pinkish legs;<ref name=HBW/> it does not exhibit sexual dimorphism.<ref name=":1">{{Cite journal |last1=Clay |first1=Thomas A. |last2=Oppel |first2=Steffen |last3=Lavers |first3=Jennifer L. |last4=Phillips |first4=Richard A. |last5=Brooke |first5=M. de L. |date=2018-12-15 |title=Divergent foraging strategies during incubation of an unusually wide-ranging seabird, the Murphy's petrel |journal=Marine Biology |volume=166 |issue=1 |page=8 |doi=10.1007/s00227-018-3451-7 |issn=0025-3162|doi-access=free |pmid=30595609 |pmc=6295288 }}</ref> It was described by [[Robert Cushman Murphy]] in 1949, which is the source of the species' common name.

Murphy's petrels take unusually long feeding trips during incubation.<ref name=":1" />

== Distribution ==
Very little is known about this species of [[petrel]]. It occurs in the South [[Pacific]], nesting on rocky [[islets]] and [[cliffs]] off tropical oceanic [[islands]] in the Austral, [[Tuamotu]], and [[Pitcairn Islands|Pitcairn]] groups.<ref name="iucn status 11 November 2021" /> It was not until the 1980s that it was determined that these petrels might be regular visitors far offshore of the west coast of North America.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=http://www.audubon.org/field-guide/bird/murphys-petrel|title=Murphy's Petrel|date=2014-11-13|newspaper=Audubon|access-date=2017-02-18|language=en}}</ref> It has been recorded off the coast of the [[Hawaiian Islands]] and well off the Pacific Coast of the [[United States]] and in the southern Gulf of Alaska.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pacificseabirdgroup.org/publications/MB_of_NOPAC/SP1993_CWS_EC_11.pdf |title=Status and ecology of gadfly petrels in the temperate North Pacific |publisher=Pacific Seabird Group |pages=101–111 }}</ref> Most reports of Murphy's petrels are over 64 km offshore<ref name=":0" /> and the species reportedly has one of the greatest foraging ranges of any breeding seabird<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.int-res.com/prepress/m12244.html|doi = 10.3354/meps12244|title = Escaping the oligotrophic gyre? The year-round movements, foraging behaviour and habitat preferences of Murphy's petrels|year = 2017|last1 = Clay|first1 = TA|last2 = Phillips|first2 = RA|last3 = Manica|first3 = A.|last4 = Jackson|first4 = HA|last5 = Brooke|first5 = Mdel|journal = Marine Ecology Progress Series|volume = 579|pages = 139–155|bibcode = 2017MEPS..579..139C|doi-access = free}}</ref>
